[[File:Thesouthblockdelhi.JPG|thumb|250px|The [[Prime Minister's Office (India)|Prime Minister Office]] in [[New Delhi|Delhi]].]]
[[File:House of the Prime Minister of Pakistan in Islamabad.jpg|thumb|250px|The Prime minister Secretariat in [[Islamabad]].]]
The '''Islamabad<U+2014>New Delhi hotline''' is a system that allows direct communication between the leaders of [[India]] and [[Pakistan]]. The hotline, according to the media sources, was established in 1971, shortly after the end of the [[Indo-Pakistani war of 1971|1971 war]].<ref name=Har-Anand>{{cite book|last=Ahmar|first=edited by Moonis|title=The challenge of confidence-building measures in South Asia|year=2001|publisher=Har-Anand|location=New Delhi, India|isbn=8124108404|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=2YSwwFp8frsC&pg=PA237&dq=new+delhi-islamabad+hotline+1971&hl=en&sa=X&ei=izK8UfLqFaS_yQGksIGQBQ&ved=0CC8QuwUwAA#v=onepage&q=new%20delhi-islamabad%20hotline%201971&f=true}}</ref><ref name="Express India, 1998">{{cite news|last=Malhotra|first=Jyoti|title=The hotline that has cooled Indo-Pak pressures|url=http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/news/ie/daily/19981024/29750024.html|accessdate=15 June 2013|newspaper=Express India, 1998|date=Saturday, October 24, 1998}}</ref>  The hotline linked the [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime minister Secretariat]] in Islamabad via [[Pakistan Army|Directorate-General of Military Operations]] (DGMO) to [[Secretariat Building, New Delhi|Secretariat Building]] in [[New Delhi]].

The hotline have seldom been used by the military leadership of [[Indian military|India]] and [[Pakistan military|Pakistan]], even at the time of an [[India Pakistan wars and conflicts|escalation of tension]]. It is also called as '''Hotline Linkage'''.<ref name=Har-Anand />  In regards to the [[Moscow<U+2013>Washington hotline]] model, the hotline serves the purpose, as both technologically and strategic rationale, for establishing the link between two counties.<ref name=Har-Anand />  The hotlines Islamabad<U+2013>Delhi hotline is a secure communication link over many procedural operations are obtained in different formats.
==History==

According the Indian media sources, the hotline was established by the governments of [[Government of India|India]] and [[Government of Pakistan|Pakistan]] shortly after the end of [[Indo-Pakistani war of 1971|1971 war]]. The Foreign ministries of [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|India]] and [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Pakistan)|Pakistan]] did signed the mutual agreement for the implementation of the hotlines.<ref name="Brookings Institution">{{cite book|last=editor|first=Janne E. Nolan,|title=Cooperation and security in the 21st century|year=1994|publisher=Brookings Institution|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=0815760981|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=-HlbZgdaa94C&pg=PA451&dq=new+delhi-islamabad+hotline+1971&hl=en&sa=X&ei=izK8UfLqFaS_yQGksIGQBQ&ved=0CDMQuwUwAQ#v=onepage&q=new%20delhi-islamabad%20hotline%201971&f=true}}</ref> The hotlines were modeled directly on [[Moscow<U+2013>Washington hotline]] which was established in 1963.<ref name=Har-Anand /> The hotline became operation 1970s after both countries' foreign ministries transmitting the messages.<ref name=Har-Anand />  

The next usage of the hotlines was in 1991 between the militaries of India and Pakistan to work on confidence-building measure.<ref name="Express India, 1998" />  The second usage of hotline was in 1997, when both countries informed each other on trade issues.<ref name="Express India, 1998" /> In 1998, during which, when both countries had publicly conducted [[nuclear test]]s, the hotlines were extensively used between the leaders of both countries.<ref name=Pearson>{{cite book|last=Thorpe|first=Edgar|title=The Pearson General Knowledge Manual|publisher=Pearson|location=New Delhi|isbn=8131761908|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=I9OyQ9mEpxkC&pg=SL3-PA46&dq=new+delhi-islamabad+hotline+1971&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qDW8UcL7BOOGyQGcg4HQDw&ved=0CEcQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=new%20delhi-islamabad%20hotline%201971&f=false|edition=10th ed.|coauthors=Thorpe, Showick}}</ref> Since 2005, the hotlines are used by each country to inform their nuclear missile tests in the region.<ref name="Asia News">{{cite news|last=AsiaNews/Agencies|title=India and Pakistan: A hotline against nuclear risk|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/India-e-Pakistan:-a-hotline-against-nuclear-risks-3899.html|accessdate=15 June 2013|newspaper=Asia News|date=August 11 2005; 09:31}}</ref>

==Other hotlines==

There are other hotlines for issues involving the [[terrorism]] (established in 2011)<ref name="Telegraph, Uk">{{cite news|last=Dean Nelson, New Delhi|title=India and Pakistan to establish counter-terrorism hotline|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/pakistan/8413946/India-and-Pakistan-to-establish-counter-terrorism-hotline.html|accessdate=15 June 2013|newspaper=Telegraph, Uk|date=4:12PM BST 29 Mar 2011}}</ref> , cyber warfare, and another hotline for record communications on prevention of the [[Nuclear Risk Reduction Center|nuclear risk]]. The nuclear hotline was setup on 20 June 2004, which was initiated by [[President of Pakistan|President]] [[Pervez Musharraf]] with the assistance of [[United States military]] officers (as an advisers) in his regime.<ref>[http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/india-and-pakistan-to-have-nuclear-hotline-732980.html ''The Independent''<U+2014>Monday, June 21, 2004--"India and Pakistan to Have Nuclear Hotline":]</ref>

